At the end of the trade, the Prague stock exchange tipped in the negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange retaliated its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the exchanges, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed its fall of the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the American financial sector, is thus also noticeable in our country.
Fall of actions in Asia
On Tuesday, the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall, even though the clues managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange's Hang Seng Index lost four per cent during trade, but later cleared some of the losses and reduced the decline to almost 2.5 per cent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange lost 3.8 per cent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney stock exchange lost more than five per cent, but ultimately the losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 per cent.
"The hesitancy about bailout action in the US will affect financial markets around the world," observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of China's central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion from Kč).
Legislators thus deny the call to support President George Bush's plan.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
The American actions had a bloodbath on Monday and the main indices of actions had experienced the greatest fall of the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced a fall of this magnitude for the last time in 1987.
The index was already lost during the vote, but when it became clear that the proposal was not adopted, it was in a free fall.
Congress gave way: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
U.S. legislators made a decisive turning point in the talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial assistance (approximately 12 trillion crowns) to the U.S. financial system.
This does not mean that success is safe.
In fact, before the Congressmans can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, they must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be reviewed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank, chair of the House's Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee.
According to sources, as early as Wednesday, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major first psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
Given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, however, there will be a "disillusion".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form that the package of measures should have for the stabilisation of the market," said Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the Bloomberg Agency.
According to her, the final vote could be taken as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, legislators met with US Finance Minister Henry Paulson to give the government a final form.
It should buy from financial companies the unsaleable real estate assets that result in significant losses to financial enterprises and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
We still need to pursue this plan to restore markets, but I think we're there," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on declining equity markets.
According to Senator Democrat Harry Reid, legislators are making sure that Congress reaches a final agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm down investors before the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress' decision could affect Monday's trade.
For the time being, it is impossible to state with certainty when the two Houses of the American Congress will proceed to the vote, nor whether the negotiations are likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by a particular problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress has the impression that the program does not perform its function, it has the possibility to block the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush praised progress in negotiations
Although the president can put his veto to this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put him in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining finance for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value shuted, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush is himself pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of Golden Parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chair Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said that legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the relief agreement, the timing of the plan.
The new law also provides for the limitation of these golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee, which will monitor the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and will be effective for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides assistance to homeowners, who have problems to pay.
The government should negotiate new down payments in the case of mortgages that it will redeem, while reducing the monthly instalments of debtors and allowing debtors to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to Patria Finance Chief Economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to achieve.
"And this is due to the fact that we don't know what the mechanism and the price will be for the buyback of problem assets.
This point will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week at server iHned.cz.
If the plan is adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
"It is much more important that the Congressmen agree, this week, that they support this plan and that they dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
An intense struggle to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put on Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl disc, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are piled vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music while moving, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories according to price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would find it difficult to support headphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just reading music, but these are, of course, unknown functions of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Besides the primary functions, phone calls and text messages, it is able to read music and films, to record them, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, serve for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are witnessing practically a miracle.
However, the universal character of mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy goingles.
Few mobiles are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, the music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly better performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you sometimes call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second reload for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
This will not be a problem for MP3 players who are able, following a reload, to operate continuously for at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without a special software.
Of course, you can record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without any reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as readers are concerned, you don't need, except for iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the performer's name, the title of the album, the style, or then according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iiver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In choosing a concrete device, be interested in the lifetime of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and the type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading MP3.
Virtually all mobiles are now capable of doing so.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to music formats that the mobile or player is able to read.
All manage to play MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have precisely this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read WMA format music.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of online music.
You just need to visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding operator's web pages (or those of another supplier) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a convincing reason for obtaining a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and in most cases is limited to fast-made radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest either.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use built-in speakers, which have virtually all the mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest normally cost less than three thousand.
For a prize of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone can control the most rudimentary readers - who do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is evident.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (M2, microSD type, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones even get away with memory cards of 8 GB.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile-walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that went the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the accumulator (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still miss something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on many occasions, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher for us than for the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this respect, Pavel Dvo­k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has stated on several occasions that in Czech Republic there was no longer room for another operator, chorus with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer very lucky (by the way, now it would find only difficult to find frequencies).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that has led to a considerable drop in prices, to which, subsequently, conventional operators must also react.
Yet, even before the entry of parties such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it became apparent that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
In addition, behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among other things the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is that it is possible to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
For example, in the world, virtual operators are emerging as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, relying on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity move.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promoting.
The launch of Mobilking will take place instead in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesman for the Penta financial group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novela Group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not for long been hiding its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to make progress in the negotiations," says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl Group.
So the future may be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not feel that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the time being, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," mentioned Vlastimil Srše+ of the press department of Telefonika O2, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate in such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to completing requests to obtain his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a drop in prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
What is the point, then, of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to get along with themselves as the larons at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also bears witness to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÚ at the time of the creation of the U:fon was that exerted by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon is ready to use as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted on this subject: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile RT market, it is clear that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, it is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
In the face of this problem, the latter adopted its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No agreement of this kind has been reached at the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said in response to our question Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS.
A statement formulated in this way would not surprise operators' representatives.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a declaration is more than confusing.
All the more so as Kristián Chalupa adds: "In other countries, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services."
However, pressure for an honest functioning of the market and lower prices is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline that is strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to chance and hard competition.
"The Office has not noticed any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecom regulator," he said in his Chaloupa statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of discord.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications are, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different vision: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, on each occasion, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
Even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding visibly in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the company GTS Novela, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to pass on to the recently adopted telecommunications law an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, there is talk of multi-level marketing firms.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special price offers (and others).
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would be examining and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question on this problem Martina Kemrová.
However, it is not likely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the mobile operators' managers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
An operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, as usual customers of mobile operators do."
That is precisely what should seem strange in the ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another question to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be content with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought about a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators tried to prevent their creation, sometimes more, sometimes less.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small, or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulators in developed countries have intervened, not in the interests of mobile operators, but in the interests of their customers.
Both formal measures and informal pressure resulted in the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are dealing with this issue in the way that a hot potato is disposed of by transmitting it to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that the confusion in skills is in these cases more than profitable.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the punch.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear at our home, the Czech mobile market may get back on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mūj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was recorded again by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Ji ' Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a choir performance and an instrumental version.
The singing is performed by Kateřina Knánková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the server iHned.cz.
Bělohlávek regards Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the performance solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that the words could be understood, that they could sing simultaneously," he said.
Next year, the Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde domov mūj first resounded in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škorup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
