Public transport (MHD) in Prague will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday.
Wednesday 1st October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Pragoise Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day coupon (this coupon will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Mřstek, Nádra+ Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letsany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons by internet on the web pages of Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can finally forget the counters in the metro stations, where they had to trample impatience in long queues so far in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon by internet and they will record it on their Opencard in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is at the disposal of the passengers a counter with trained staff, who will help those interested with the purchase by internet and, moreover, will record the coupon they bought on their card," says the spokesperson of the Martin Opatrný project.
Next to the libraries, it will also be possible to record electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," added Optrný.
A automaton will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow, are easy to use.
Simply insert the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
