The Sudeten called for a referendum in the USA
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans demanded that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some Sudeten German groups allegedly addressed the US president with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov in the letter ask the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemian) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Šumava cares".
Since the rallying to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only brutality, disrespectful attitude, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would have only to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the then Sudeten Germans.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to gain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him for him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the Germans captured who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, felt that, following the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
