Insomnia nights for Hypo Real Estate shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), side of the DAX, obtains a billion credit from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
One person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are granted up to EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
Money comes from both private and public-law banks.
In the background, it is the Depfa daughter company that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since the mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to EUR 2.37 million, and the own capital rate had also slightly weakened from 1.6 to 1.45 per cent.
The current and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero from the same period in the previous year, the profits from the allocation of specified receivables and securities and the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen from more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only through the large profits from the repayment of the downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as from the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies, that the earnings deficit of about 16 per cent proved to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had initially miscured on industrial loans for real estate, which had subsequently been transferred to Aareal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa had subsequently become more involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of joint projects between private investors and the state (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, the Hypo Real Estate must carry out depreciations which should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect which remains nevertheless rather vague.
The fact is the dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated by two thirds.
Since the acquisition of the Depfa, the Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the inter-bank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks again became considerably timid, with banks having accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing average of around 50 billion euros per year for all Depfa credits.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the Group's financing requirement is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets which are currently largely out of order.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
The Chairman of the Executive Board of HRE Georg Funke, on the other hand, explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to financial markets in the medium term.
The Federal Bank and the Federal Institution for the Supervision of Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the capacity of the Hypo Real Group in the market is now assured.
The bank's shareholders and creditors can only hope for this.
However, in view of the dynamics and unweightedness of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that funding should not be used in its entirety.
But neither can the opposite be ruled out.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest communiqués, still at the door of insolvency Sunday at the end of the evening, this rescue for the least temporary will not succeed in reassuring the minds either.
The share price fell from 75 per cent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are particularly good.
While debt in the first place has barely moved, the prices of second-rate loans are declining.
The most affected are the investment funds of the former daughter company Württemberg Hypo and of course those which have a lifetime beyond 2009.
The bonds of the bank Hypo Real Estate previously seemed to be an alternative speculation investment, now their value must be considered dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the net tightening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the very institute which brought the crisis into the establishment by the acquisition of the bank Depfa.
As long as the issuing institutes, governments and less affected commercial banks are still ready to support the system, it can be assumed that arrears will be reduced over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares to hope at this moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But in the face of the renewed noises of partial nationalization, the probability that approached safety has now become a simple, well-founded hope.
This should reserve nights of insomnia first and foremost for long-term creditors on whether to separate themselves from their commitments.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn a line on to represent a carry-over of losses for the next few years to the next tax on capital income from automatically collected stock gains.
