Speaking in sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I do not refer to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time this happens may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquia.
This is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who's talking at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep alterations such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (pee in bed) or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcitation.
Anyway, it's a little studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
He may speak with a quiet little voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with shouts, tears, long speeches ...
In the event that somniloquia becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment, unless it is related to another alteration of sleep that can be treated (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV shows that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who are struggling to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleeping pills appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
It's useless because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even if he speaks, he sleeps and rests.
Remember that if it is very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor or check what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not have the temptation to question him for information.
You won't get anything, because by sleeping, he's not conscious to be able to organize his thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so pay attention to how you interpret the information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him during the night to know his secrets.
Not even joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
