The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr.Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Most importantly, he regained the public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the grunt of the public, in February 1994 the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not occur again.
While Justice Krever was slow to table his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, just 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was disheartening.
As a result of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
Since its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there were many cases in Europe of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious disease can result, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
As a result, in April 1999, blood was refused for people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique emerged on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
The NATs made it possible to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowing it and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health," says the Chief Executive Officer of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year appeared on Reunion Island the Chikungunya virus which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Because anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets to recharge.
The aging population also has an impact on the blood donor network, which averages only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
A healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria can still give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since today's life is so unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye globes and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is full of stem cell-rich blood that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing some for transplants at the beginning of next year," says Dr.Decary, who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it", because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
