Free opinion - The Orwellian speech of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has brought a six million libel suit against three authors and a small publishing house without a penny in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of Black Canada will have to spend considerable money to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactics, in these unequal struggles, are often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look back at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was therefore enough for mining to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he could both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to fatly paid lawyers, not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is prepared to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag chase (following the "public debate", Barrick Gold has also just filed a warning against Black Canada authors intimidating them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal discourse, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the quest for truth, essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to the citation of credible sources and the debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, or if there are no repeated prosecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has a long history of managing debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
The disproportionate pursuit of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the academic world, as well as to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abuse.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default, and a right of scrutiny of the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on the daily lives of Americans will be huge," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on investors' mood.
The deadline was for the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that it was necessary to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has attributed the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the agreement to allow owners to keep their homes and the agreement on the salaries of the executives of companies that have been rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The broad lines I have read [show] that this is something we are all going to have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the bad, risky and unsaleable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble which first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and leading to a freezing of liquidity and the debandade of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of elected Republicans who blew the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been overcome since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round off the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision has also been added stating that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion, to which the President may add another 100 billion if he deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be approved by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain shares in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil passes.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance payments paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
In fact, voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democrat camp.
"Obviously, Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one which consists of profiting the taxpayers".
Moderator of a small group in Congress, nicknamed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic representative Brad Sherman presented things differently, but came to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and to look carefully at the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas had indicated that it had renounced to acquire its competitor in full shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85 000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"It's not lost money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In return, we get back a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that the times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on the way to nationalising another bank misled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion (US 75.5 billion) would be real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the branches and accounts receivable of the British bank.
The Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time his asset card, some will say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent flowing from the source will also have removed him from the power register that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
But what a great runner!
Paul Newman, who disappeared Friday, at the age of 83, as a result of lung cancer in his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the fastes years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of which he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his game, certainly more fragile, but also apostle of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
The mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother of origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, the ultimate brand of quality.
Because in him there was a whole country that loved the self-made man, the Pacific War fighter, wounded in combat, who at the beginning of the 1950s studied dramatic art at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in theatre, on television, soon in cinema.
The same man who militated for civil rights was also the motor driver who finished second in the 24 hours of Le Mans in 1979, coupled with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadow zones of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the brilliance of the show-business, of which we will not have completely pierced the enigma.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman's disappearance brought vertigo to the movies this weekend, as his big roles clashed on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual mutation unfolds through it.
Return to memory of the charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in La Chatte on a burning roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises, was evoked.
So many other Paul Newmans have come to history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me, by Robert Wise, a role for James Dean, taken over after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This nice thug in the brilliant The Sting (L'Arnaque), Oscar of the best film in 1973.
A bitter billiard player and avenger in the magnificent Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), he took over the character on the return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar in 1987 on nine nominations.
That face through the ages was him.
He's still here.
The eras rushed through his path.
Young people know him mostly through George Roy Hill's Slap Shot (1977) in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
With a final role as sponsor of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
In contrast to several legends of the cinema that left the trade early on, Newman will have remained in saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its fastes and its concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humour, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" considering his performances too supported.
The profession has not always been tender for the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles long fell all cooked in the beak.
However, he played less often the young first than the marginals: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect features reflected drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed little known facets of his true modest sensitivity.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (according to the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine feminine portrait of melancholy.
He lost his son Scott by overdose and dedicated his film Harry and Son in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rains of tributes that broke out yesterday on Newman, his great friend and former arms companion Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generousness, love of existence are vibrant features of the disappeared actor.
Beyond his career as a legend, he also erases a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of Hollywood drifts.
We've seen a lot of his dick standing on vinaigrette pots, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process to be rather bad taste, though gag at first.
However, the profits from these sales were paid to his Foundation for Children in Difficulty.
Newman, rather than sit on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: "Always and until the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
