And a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in sum and in addition.
What could Zuschlag &amp; Company make in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly serious damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as, for example, forgery and the use of forgery.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The money of the state and the municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, which was also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing bills of fees, behind which no actual services were provided and thus the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they bought invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to his testimony, he had to spot pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among others, from the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlags in 2003, this place restored a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
In the same way, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which will later be named Együtt to Harmadik Evezredért, was gruelling with faults of form and substance.
A boarding house, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
Imagining bill issuers also fell into excess, when they mentioned Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of Hoppá appeared, according to the information given to the prosecutor's office.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a bad place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people have lodged there, also did not stick, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The issuers of zealous invoices also did not ask themselves about the Budapest travel agencies, which were part of their choice, but organized only trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
From a surprise, as it appeared during the survey, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices issued in the name of the Hotel Revfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a 25% VAT as indicated, but a 15% VAT. Moreover, the employees of the hotel issue only printed invoices, while the fakes were written by hand.
The prosecution's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as a supply the carriage of goods by road, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment consultancy.
Moreover, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont have proved to be false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó sports training course, which both deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation when (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Invoices deliberately established
Another category of invoice issuers is that composed of those who were fully aware that they were asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esely Budapestert Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the group of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has established an invoice to the order of the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for a sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület Association and Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but behind which no services were actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the organizations in their accounts.
The next category of invoice companies is that of companies directly related to the accused.
For example, the executive director of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where it could not be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he seized their value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies functioned, which the accused explains because they did not receive work.
He nevertheless used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-defendant as well as editor of the founding documents of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave agencies, 15 invoices in total, issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the amounts shown on the invoices as well as VAT went in Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used in the application for a grant from Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért Association applied to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA) for a grant from the public utility body of the Socialist Party.
They obtained this grant for a sum of HUF 500,000 twice, but these amounts were not used for the objectives indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will report on the method of making invoices, as they had already done before the prosecution.
What might be really interesting is that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has promised several times to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or, possibly, the Socialists would have reached an agreement that, in exchange for the repayment of much of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would bear the hat alone.
Today, he is probably offended, as requests for house arrest, on the basis of a reduction in his conditions of detention, continually fall into the ears of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and those who commit unreparable economic crimes, walk freely or at least, wait at their own home for the end of the proceedings. He does not have this possibility.
The psychology of the overbid: why are we spending more money?
During auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, one essential element of which is the over-biding of a third party, the whole under the brain stem, called striatum, was moving intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight in front of the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
At the time, three groups were overbiding by a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus made their investments.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win the game, then they would receive an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auction, the members of the group also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was placed in one group on victory, while in the other, on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to wager higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When do we need to see a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
Patients with hepatitis virus in Hungary are estimated at one hundred miles, but only seven miles are being treated. This is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but pathogens and diseases are different from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended that they be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach aches and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients is receiving medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know of the virus, because the pathogenic gene destroys the liver cells in a sneaky way. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult with your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does the one who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph has published an article according to which researchers at Oxford University have made an interesting experiment by analysing at what level belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also possible to discover that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academicians, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing the electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to watch two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four parts succeeding, while looking either at the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics said that, in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "safe", as someone "cared for" and they "calmed, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that we can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that we find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, like, for example, a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, praised the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases actually changes our personality," added Wright.
After these excellent results, only the question remains of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if one shows believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would the sight of a better Virgin Mary produce better results?
