According to the Google leader interviewed, after ten years of global shattering, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
To the question: what will happen in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What would be the best job for me?". However, the software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first sight, when they know enough about the users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer launching the search, and the pages consulted by the interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they've been looking for, on which they clicked. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and our registered preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if he looks at what my job is? ask users, who are worried about Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can generate fear, and it is not the remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom, or possibly revolt against power that can trigger a counter-reaction among Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing an identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users may have sighed for relief last May, when Google, with EFF's e-legal protection agency, proved its right in court against the FBI. According to the judgment rendered, in the future, Google will still not be forced by any of the points of the constitution to disclose information about the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, it fails to get the lists of searches of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is castigated by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and their private domain suffer from it when they begin to use Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savageons" bringing together enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the "connected corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, catalogued as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The document code and package of programs, continually refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, compared to the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what web 2.0, the most proclaimed key word of recent years, is pulling right behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 does not concern anything other than collaboration, than the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the channels of communication made available to us, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can hold a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other performances, such as Twinter, or last.fm, which is a link to his musical habits. Then, he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which they automatically appear their most recent photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can see many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands from the pictures of the morning, taken by the circle of friends who shared, with whom his unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that fired one of his employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, we can be sure of one thing: the term of privacy is totally to be reconsidered nowadays.
He who lives an online life is made up of what he shows of himself, and that is how we can define the principle hiding behind the behaviour of today's young people.
Whoever wants to hide something, or at least wants to try to bypass Google's monopoly, can do it (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using Google's search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not the least. Google’s online services, through word processing to image processing and reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge server parks and which do not assemble our best profile, which have existed to date.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its present value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising fields threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other creators of computer programs.
However, critical observers find contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management refused, in its entirety, the protests of employees, after it doubled the price of the kindergarten and after the company deemed the daily multiple catering, taken at any time, too expensive. All this seems ridiculous in addition to the fact that already in 2006, Google acquiesced before the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that injure the good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is sure is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that Google's project of scanning and archiving books and magazines takes on such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing the Supreme Court of the United States, others are shaking in front of its Health system, because in it, we can build a complete medical profit from our results of previous analyses, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is setting up a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction authors. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with orwellian half-tones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google's data.
