Smart car mimics bourdon theft
What method would be better to develop technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, other than the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like, for example, bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, held in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic idea of starting, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired auto-roboted system, type BR23C, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate objective being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
On its flights, each bee constitutes its own oval-shaped space, which in fact looks very much like our secure protective hull - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the technological research and development and public relations department of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of a laser ranger.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it with a sufficient angle to avoid the collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the mini robot could not react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment collision is considered inevitable.
All this process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we were able to use only the rotary motion, acceleration and slowing down as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini robot
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a greater concentration of energy, making their lifetime longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, instinctive intelligent reaction is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism must deal with only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant-avoidance technology. Nissan estimates that this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
