The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue plan, aimed at redeeming banks' doubtful credit and using it in multiple ways, is ready.
In the first round, half of this amount will be spent.
Reuters announces that in the course of further debates lasting until after midnight, Saturday, local time on the east coast, the leaders of Congress have agreed on the controversies existing for days and days, around the rescue plan for a total amount of $700 billion.
"We have taken a serious step forward" - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the American House of Representatives, according to which the only thing left is to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, commented on the outcome of the compromise that the program will work and will be effective, but other measures still need to be implemented. Pelosi says that there is no question here of saving Wall Street, but of turning the machinery of the economy in the other direction.
The written version of the plan was made public before the opening of the Asian markets, Sunday evening at 8 p.m., local time in Washington (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to local time in Central Europe), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill in the name of the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008. Then, its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday evening, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are satisfied with the progress achieved tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, White House spokesman.
In addition, the program diverges from the Bush administration's original proposal, which stated that the $700 billion had to be spent on a one-time basis, for the purchase of securities for doubtful credits.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be issued immediately after Congress passes the law, probably on Monday. This first amount will be used by the Treasury Secretary to purchase bad debts from banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the President's discretion.
The program will be overseen by an independent organization, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also take part.
The expenditure of the second half of the 700 billion depends on a new decree of Congress.
According to the law, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to put in place a combined strategy: at the same time, it will be able to purchase bad debts, securities relating to bad mortgages and bad mortgages, as well as other types of "toxic" debts.
The appropriate persons in the department have stated that buybacks may take place in the context of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance programme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools at the root of the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated that the law provides the necessary tools to spend $700 billion for the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it is the vast redemption of doubtful claims, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of seeing the system leading to the collapse of one or the other important financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements, to be ready for the application of the law, as soon as it is signed" - he added.
On the other hand, the leaders of banks in poor positions and waiting for state aid can expect their severance pay, simply called the gold parachute across the Atlantic, to be capped by the government.
Wage limits are mentioned only in specific cases, and limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat provides assistance to the company.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury Secretariat buys back in an auction, they will levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the redemption of the bad debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
In order for the image to be complete, it must nevertheless be added that the existing golden parachutes are not changed. The cap only concerns new contracts, this to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal ceilings will be in place on the back-up of directors general - commented the chairman of the committee in charge of financial services of the Chamber of Deputies, the Democratic Barney Frank.
In addition, the state acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks taking part in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers diminishes, since they can even win in the case as soon as the economy and with it the saved banks will fall on their feet.
The bill mentions that in the next five years, the President must bring a proposal to Congress that will decide how the losses will be returned to taxpayers, from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens mandated us, it doesn't protect taxpayers' dollars - said California's Republican MP Darrell Issa.
His fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, believes that it is the same people who are urging action, as those responsible for the Wall Street collapse.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reported by the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent compared to the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic selling prices in the processing industry sectors experienced only a tiny 0.1 per cent increase over July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), primarily with the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by the production of footwear with 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
Higher prices for plastics and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly rise in prices in the chemical and chemical manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
Deflation resulted in oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and apparatus manufacturing (0.9 per cent), and a minimal increase in wood processing (0.1 per cent).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry saw an increase, ranging from 0.2 to 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial operations, prices increased by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly because of the rise in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, the oil processing sector's prices showed the most significant increase (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2 per cent, while in the important area of food production, beverages and tobacco, prices rose by 11 per cent.
There have been price reductions in the textile and textile products production sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6 per cent to 9.1 per cent.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to the sector allocation, in August, it was the leading sectors of investment profit that showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7%).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and material-producing sectors for subsequent processing did not change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and material production sectors for further processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-generating sectors, it was 1.4 per cent.
Export prices of the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In a month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 per cent against the euro, and by 7.1 per cent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent against the euro and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
