Járóka said: The vicious cycle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today, in Paris, the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, began as a representative of the current Presidency of the European Union.
In his message to the plenary assembly, as one of the main spokesmen of the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is a violation of the law that most affects Roma children and thus one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, this high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Among those invited to take part in the consultation are the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of legal protection and European civil bodies, in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the group of deputy Fidesz Parti Populaire, Járóka warned that, in addition to the distinctions made during the hirings, Roma disappear from the labour market, in the first place, as a result of their low qualifications.
"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have high school diplomas, and as a result of poor quality elementary education, only a tiny part has the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in upholding other fundamental rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economies of EU member countries.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relations in the broadest possible circle, also between Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the more likely he or she is to become a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from his or her income and consumption, he or she participates in the State budget.
"By virtue of their citizenship of the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - stressed Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, collaboration by the European Union towards an objective and action is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools. To this end, compliance with existing and in preparation anti-discrimination directives is of paramount importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and the unemployed; we must give the opportunities provided by democracy to Roma children, so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - demanded Járóka.
In the name of the "European Year for Equal Opportunities" for all, the objective of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe, organised every year since the Berlin Summit last year, is to ensure a single platform to support measures taken to promote equal opportunities and to combat discrimination, targeted at European level and at Member State level.
