Mp3 reader pointed at their finger, they put the hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period using portable musical devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing damage.
This is what the European Commission, which, in a press release in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee on unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) published today.
"of this scientific report- we read in the note- it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable musical devices, for more than one hour per day per week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable musical devices and mobile phones at full volume may unconsciously damage their hearing irreparably," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data- continues the manager Ue- this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What is most important is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
We must also review existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can monitor new technologies."
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists-concluded the executive Ue- confirm that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now examine with the Member States and other interested parties, what possible measures could be taken to better protect children and adolescents against exposure to noise from portable musical devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical devices to 100Db, but there is increasing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to limit these data well using solutions such as reduction of noise levels and duration of exposure.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable musical devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level at the workplace.
Those who listen to music under such conditions for extended periods of time are at risk of permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified in about 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
