The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the House of Representatives voting, contrary to the 700 billion dollar bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms to us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its moderate soul East Coast, favorable to federal institutions as well as to business community, and its new soul, conservative, hostile to "the ones of Washington" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, which was despotically felt with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been cited is only an example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake pre-announces or already leaves running: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and can be not just here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to have accelerated the phenomena that have arisen for some time now, so much so that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereign, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with the foreigner, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it is governed: that is to say, to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation really seems out of hand, or it does not have much to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, manages to decide no common political lines.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a affection of credit: when we go through a difficult period, there are only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-important importance that the more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized from a single stroke, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with things that are not material enough such as water, crops, oil.
Things which can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than the one who is not, that is, the one who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty, which nevertheless foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who can take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadowy areas.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their apogee, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, The demand for leadership, nourishes underground, a powerful and branched movement of delegitimassions of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the improvised electoral "rebellions" or in the collective changes of recent times, starting from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, the fall of the Labourers in Great Britain, the rebellion of the American Congressists against Bush (and it might well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, would say someone, have ever more difficulty, which is not today's date, in understanding and thus representing the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening, increasing and potentially agitating in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, talking about a current "mass rebellion" on the agenda seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said well, keeping your eyes wide open is not without reason.
The superglue to walk on the walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity thanks to a super glue and, in the future, walk on the walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centres, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimetres, the researchers managed to hold a 100 kg body on a vertical wall.
ETUDE- The American journal Science published the findings of researchers from Dayton University, Akron, Georgia Institute of Technology and Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know who use a particular carbon structure, called nano carbon tubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged as a stack of spaghetti." Explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have drawn inspiration from the legs of the geckos, covered in microscopic hairs that ensure the animal, a perfect adherent.
Tests carried out on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass paper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times more powerful than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time that it "is easily detached from the wall", explains Liming Dai, researcher of the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
MARKETING ON MURSE? –"this material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as connection between electronic devices, since nano carbon tubes are conductors of heat and electric current.
Other applications may include aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
THE OTHER RESEARCH- The University of Berkeley, California, is also dedicated to the search for a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, Californian researchers presented an adhesive made of microfibres like hair, which cleans dust during movement on an area to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are detoxifying and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter the absorption amplifying or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of juices, whether in cans or fresh, associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launched a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, cancelling their beneficial effects and putting patients at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticized as being responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-statinal and neurological drugs to toxic levels.
MEDICINAL PRODUCTS - It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a two-year newsletter, alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mix and to pay attention to what they drink, if they take medicines such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT THAT PAMPLEMOUSSE- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active substances inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the call of Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department of the Public University of Milan: "These discoveries are generally reported immediately to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the information notes of the medicines if necessary.
It is always appropriate to read the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," stressed the expert to the Ansa agency.
