A forecast that unleashed many controversies, and which was blamed on the economist for years, but which has now proved to be accurate.
"I am surprised and even a little shocked at the speed with which the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom, disappeared from the public's attention," Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Executive Committee of the European Central Bank, Krugman is a "high-value economist" but also a very aggressive "disclosure", particularly critical of the Bush administration's excesses of liberalism.
