Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market does not experience a crisis
According to the last survey of the Sunia, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euro in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding whole categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support- explains the head of the study office of Sunia, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has distorted the market so much that a process of widespread increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, there are also a number of violations in the rental offers: free, unregistered, rent-free contracts, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of tax taxation are necessary to calm prices.
Read in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it ranges from 650 euros minimum (Band Nere area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate area, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria area)
In Florence, an average bed costs 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (€550 for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save only if you move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, we spend from 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by extra-Community students, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the cities elect the historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favour of the Multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image presented by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of large multi-salles, and the death of the consumption of mono-salles in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inescapable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historic places and filled with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of a path and so much emotion," observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and that told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way to live cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have mainly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Romaine Emilia is in the lead with 82 single theatre cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof which confirms that the first person responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-salle cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observed Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a firm hall in a city, these frequentors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the missed deliberation of credit in favour of traders: the state's antecedent debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government is not complying with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between €16 million and €18 million per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between Town Hall and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the single cinemas of the historic centres and on the outskirts.
Among the normative measures envisaged are measures of fiscal facilities for managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special rates for parking and in certain parking lots.
"This is an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna with other measures in place.
It is clear, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New cinema Paradiso" to which I had already thought for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn on the other side so that I do not see the signs darkened by the dust.
