When the energy comes from the waves, now the big ones start.
This is an oversized deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface area and now the world's largest energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which colossians like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now are trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has now been explored for a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil lowered, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was set aside, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea swell operating systems.
This amount would be twice that of nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides..
Colossus in attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy was the Energis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the deal was announced, it seemed like a real revolutionary step.
With two years of this, more and more candidates among these companies dedicated to traditional energy have always relied on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying technologies on ocean energy- said a spokesman for a company associated with the American oil colossus, the economic daily Wall Street Journal- and she is assessing the possibilities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the Usa continue to extract oil, and recently President Bush set up a project for further excavations.
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which travel the route of energy coming from the sea, and the sums invested so far, although their details are not known, according to observers, show an increasing interest.
Tecnology to be developed.
Experts are talking about a technology still in its early stages, because marine energy does not dispel fears about the environmental impact.
At present, systems such as those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size and do not seem to create a major problem for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, however, technologies need to be used with a higher environmental impact.
" And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the sludge upwards and downwards, is converted into a hydraulic pressure of the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
Pressure drives a turbine that, in turn, powers a generator.
The energy is sent to the shore through underwater cables.
For the time being, we have four such systems in the project phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
